Donatus, and after him most com- mentators pronounce that either ⁴ utrum' or ‘ ne ' is superfluous ; or that the form ⁴ utrumne ’ is here separated by tmesis. Neither explanation is right in this passage. ⁴ Utrum ' is here used as a pronoun followed by a disjunctive question. Compare Plautus, Captivi ii. 2. 18:

‘⁴ Sed utrum strictimne attonsumm dicam esse an per pectinem Nescio ;''

Pseudolus ii. 4. 19: ‘⁴ Dic, utrum Spemne an Salutem te salutem Pseudole ?'' and Terence, Adelphi iii. 3. 28:

The ordinary explanation has arisen from the fact that we sometimes find ‘ nam' or ‘ ne’ added to ‘utrum ’ in emphatic ques- tions, 55 they are to other interrogative words.
